oc:kn_1cbdd9ba a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating or editing SKILL.md" ;
    oc:directiveContent "SKILL.md must include YAML frontmatter with required 'name' and 'description' fields. The description determines when Claude triggers the skill—be specific with exact user phrases." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Without proper frontmatter, skills cannot be discovered or triggered by Claude Code" ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_677a8043 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating skills for Claude Code plugins" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For plugin skills, place skills in plugin-name/skills/skill-name/ directory. Plugin skills are distributed as part of the plugin, not as separate ZIP files. Claude Code auto-discovers skills by scanning the skills/ directory for subdirectories containing SKILL.md." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Plugin skills follow a different distribution model than standalone skills and don't need packaging scripts" .

oc:kn_68d69c0c a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:WorkflowStrategy ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating any new skill" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Follow the six-step skill creation process in order, skipping steps only with clear justification: (1) Understand use cases with concrete examples, (2) Plan reusable resources, (3) Create directory structure, (4) Write/edit SKILL.md and resources, (5) Validate and test, (6) Iterate based on usage." ;
    oc:hasRationale "The sequential process ensures skills are well-designed, properly scoped, and tested before use" .

oc:kn_7b242270 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When organizing skill content" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Information must live in either SKILL.md or references files, not both. Avoid duplication across files. Keep only essential procedural instructions in SKILL.md; move detailed reference material, schemas, and examples to references/." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Duplication wastes context window tokens and creates maintenance burden when information changes" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_984afc74 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:KnownIssue ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When validating or reviewing skills" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Common skill quality problems: weak trigger descriptions (vague, no specific phrases), bloated SKILL.md (>3,000 words without references), second-person writing style, unreferenced resource files, and broken/incomplete examples." ;
    oc:hasRationale "These are the most frequent issues found in skill development and the primary causes of poor skill performance" .

oc:kn_9ee00cd7 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing skill frontmatter descriptions" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never use vague trigger descriptions like 'Provides guidance for X' or 'Load when user needs X'. Always include specific trigger phrases with concrete user queries: 'This skill should be used when the user asks to \"create X\", \"configure Y\"'" ;
    oc:hasRationale "Vague descriptions fail to trigger skills when users need them, making skills invisible to the system" ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_b617fe84 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing or editing any skill" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Skills use three-level progressive disclosure: (1) Metadata (name + description) always in context (~100 words), (2) SKILL.md body loaded when skill triggers (<5k words), (3) Bundled resources loaded as needed by Claude (unlimited). Keep SKILL.md lean at 1,500-2,000 words; move detailed content to references/." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Progressive disclosure prevents context window bloat while ensuring detailed information is discoverable when needed" ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_cab2173a a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing any skill content" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never write skills in second person ('you should', 'you need to'). Always use imperative/infinitive form ('To accomplish X, do Y') and third-person in frontmatter descriptions ('This skill should be used when...')." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Second-person writing introduces ambiguity for AI consumption and breaks consistency across skills" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:req_430ee7da a oc:RequirementKnowledge ;
